009/**
010 * Allows for the use of custom colors with custom names.
011 * <p>
012 * These colors are comparable for equality but the ordering of them is based on
013 * their hex values.
014 * <p>
015 * Has some built in palettes available as SColor arrays.
016 *
017 * @author Eben Howard - http://squidpony.com - howard@squidpony.com
018 * @see SquidColorCenter Another way to manage colors if you don't want to use preallocated instances.
019 */
020public class SColor extends Color {

6409    /**
6410     * An array of SColor values that should all be fairly different from any other in the group.
6411     * This may be useful for tinting things that should be color-coded differently from each other. To get a random
6412     * order for these colors while still guaranteeing that no color will be drawn twice in the first 56 choices, you
6413     * can use {@code OrderedSet<SColor> palette = new OrderedSet<SColor>(SColor.VARIED_PALETTE).shuffle(rng);} (where
6414     * rng is any non-null RNG) and then get sequential colors from that set with
6415     * {@code int i = 0; SColor color = palette.getAt(i);} , incrementing i before calling getAt again and possibly
6416     * wrapping with {@code i %= 56;} .
6417     * This includes 56 colors, organized in groups of 4 from dark to light in each group:
6418     * <ul>
6419     *     <li>0-3: gray group</li>
6420     *     <li>4-7: brown group</li>
6421     *     <li>8-11: red group</li>
6422     *     <li>12-15: pink group</li>
6423     *     <li>16-19: magenta/purple group</li>
6424     *     <li>20-23: purple/blue-ish group</li>
6425     *     <li>24-27: darker blue group</li>
6426     *     <li>28-31: lighter blue and blue-green group</li>
6427     *     <li>32-35: pure green group</li>
6428     *     <li>36-39: grayish-green group</li>
6429     *     <li>40-43: yellow-green group</li>
6430     *     <li>44-47: yellow group</li>
6431     *     <li>48-51: orange group</li>
6432     *     <li>52-55: orange-red-pink/salmon/coral group</li>
6433     * </ul>
6434     */
6435    public static final SColor[] VARIED_PALETTE = {
6436            DARK_GRAY, GRAY, LIGHT_GRAY, DB_EGGSHELL,
6437            DB_SEAL_BROWN, BROWNER, DARK_TAN, TAN,
6438            DB_BLOOD, PURE_CRIMSON, RED, IBIS_WING,
6439            TREE_PEONY, DEEP_CERISE, HOT_PINK, PINK,
6440            INDIGO, PURPLE, PSYCHEDELIC_PURPLE, LIGHT_VIOLET,
6441            ROYAL_PURPLE, VIOLET, HALF_PURPLE, LAVENDER_FLORAL,
6442            COBALT, CERULEAN_BLUE, BLUE, CORNFLOWER_BLUE,
6443            LIGHT_BLUE_FLOWER, ROBIN_EGG_BLUE, CYAN, LIGHT_BLUE,
6444            GREEN_BAMBOO, PERSIAN_GREEN, ELECTRIC_GREEN, MINT_GREEN,
6445            CAMO_GREEN, PALE_GREEN_ONION, PASTEL_GREEN, MOSS_GREEN,
6446            OLIVE_DRAB, YELLOW_GREEN, CHARTREUSE_GREEN, ELECTRIC_LIME,
6447            GOLD, SCHOOL_BUS_YELLOW, YELLOW, LEMON_CHIFFON,
6448            BURNT_ORANGE, OCHRE, CAPE_JASMINE, PEACH_YELLOW,

6638    /**
6639     * A constructor with no passed values. Builds a white (opaque all channels)
6640     * object.
6641     */
6642    public SColor() { //builds white
6643        this(Color.rgb888(Color.WHITE));
6644    }
6645
6646    /**
6647     * Creates a new color that's the same value as the passed in color.
6648     *
6649     * @param color
6650     */
6651    public SColor(Color color) {
6652        this(Color.rgb888(color));
6653    }
6654
6655    /**
6656     * Creates a new color that's the same value as the passed in color and
6657     * given the provided name.
6658     *
6659     * @param color
6660     * @param name
6661     */
6662    public SColor(Color color, String name) {
6663        this(Color.rgb888(color));
6664        this.name = name;
6665    }
6666
6667    /**
6668     * Creates a new color that has the given combined RGB value.
6669     *
6670     * @param colorValue
6671     */
6672    public SColor(int colorValue) {
6673        super((colorValue << 8) | 255);
6674        name = super.toString();
6675    }
6676
6677    /**
6678     * Creates a new color that has the given combined RGB value and the
6679     * provided name.
6680     *
6681     * @param colorValue
6682     * @param name
6683     */
6684    public SColor(int colorValue, String name) {
6685        super((colorValue << 8) | 255);
6686        this.name = name;
6687    }
6688
6689    /**
6690     * Creates a new color that has the given RGB values.
6691     *
6692     * @param r
6693     * @param g
6694     * @param b
6695     */
6696    public SColor(int r, int g, int b) {
6697        super(r / 255f, g / 255f, b / 255f, 1.0f);
6698        name = super.toString();
6699    }
6700
6701    /**
6702     * Creates a new color that has the given ARGB values.
6703     *
6704     * @param r
6705     * @param g
6706     * @param b
6707     * @param a
6708     */
6709    public SColor(int r, int g, int b, int a) {
6710        super(r / 255f, g / 255f, b / 255f, a / 255f);
6711        name = super.toString();
6712    }
6713
6714    /**
6715     * Creates a new color that has the given RGB values and the provided name.
6716     *
6717     * @param r

6763    /**
6764     * Use {@link #intToFloatColor(int)} instead, it's twice as fast on desktop, but still 3x slower than the JDK method
6765     * {@link Float#intBitsToFloat(int)}. {@link com.badlogic.gdx.utils.NumberUtils#intToFloatColor(int)} is now
6766     * super-sourced on GWT with a drastically simpler replacement than the original GWT code, and will use the JDK's
6767     * implementation on desktop where it is much faster, so using NumberUtils should be the way to go.
6768     * @param bits the int to convert to float; only bits in the mask 0xfeffffff will be used
6769     * @return the float that can be used to represent the given bits
6770     */
6771    public static float intToFloatColorAlt(final int bits)
6772    {
6773        return (1f - (bits >>> 30 & 2)) * (0x1.0p0f + 0x0.000002p0f * (bits & 0x7fffff)) *
6774                ((bits & 0x40000000) == 0
6775                        ? (((bits >> 29 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-64f) * ((bits >> 28 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-32f) * ((bits >> 27 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-16f) * ((bits >> 26 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-8f) * ((bits >> 25 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-4f) * 0x1.0p-2f * ((bits >> 23 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-1f))
6776                        : (((bits >> 29 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p64f : 1) * ((bits >> 28 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p32f : 1) * ((bits >> 27 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p16f : 1) * ((bits >> 26 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p8f : 1) * ((bits >> 25 & 1) == 1 ? 0x1.0p4f : 1) * 0x1.0p2f * ((bits >> 23 & 1) == 1 ? 1 : 0x1.0p-1f))
6777                );
6778    }
6779    /**
6780     * Possible replacement for {@link NumberUtils#intToFloatColor(int)} that is much less complex on GWT; shouldn't be
6781     * called directly and you should default to {@link com.badlogic.gdx.utils.NumberUtils#intToFloatColor(int)}. That
6782     * method is now super-sourced on GWT with a this method as a much simpler replacement for the original GWT code,
6783     * but will not replace the JDK's implementation on desktop where it is much faster. Using NumberUtils should be the
6784     * way to go. For reference, see GWT's source for {@link Float#intBitsToFloat(int)},
6785     * https://gwt.googlesource.com/gwt/+/2.8.0/user/super/com/google/gwt/emul/java/lang/Float.java#96 ,
6786     * which involves multiple if statements, temporary variables, creates a long (slow on GWT), and finally passes off
6787     * control to another method. There's also {@link #rgbToFloatColor(int)} if you don't need to worry about alpha.
6788     *
6789     * @param bits the int to convert to float; only bits in the mask 0xfeffffff will be used
6790     * @return the float that can be used to represent the given bits
6791     */
6792    public static float intToFloatColor(final int bits)
6793    {
6794        return (1 - (bits >>> 30 & 2)) * (1f + 0x0.000002p0f * (bits & 0x7fffff)) *
6795                multipliers[(bits >> 24 & 0x7e) | (bits >> 23 & 1)];
6796    }
6797    public static float rgbToFloatColor(final int rgb)
6798    {
6799        return -(0x1.0p125f + 0x0.000002p125f * (rgb & 0x7fffff)) * ((rgb >> 23 & 1) + 1);
6800    }
6801
6802    /**
6803     * Modifies the color parameter {@code changing} so its value is the one encoded in {@code value}. The way to
6804     * obtain value for libGDX Color objects is with {@link Color#toFloatBits()}, which uses ABGR order, so this
6805     * does some quick work to convert that to RGBA order and assign that into changing.
6806     * @param changing a Color object that will be modified to have the given value
6807     * @param value a value as a float that can be obtained by {@link Color#toFloatBits()}
6808     * @return
6809     */
6810    public static Color colorFromFloat(Color changing, float value)
6811    {
6812        return changing.set(Integer.reverseBytes(NumberUtils.floatToIntColor(value)));
6813    }
6814    static final char[] digits = {
6815            '0', '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6', '7',
6816            '8', '9', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F'};
6817
6818    /**
6819     * Stores the value of color in the char[] {@code changing}, using RGBA8888 format with two hex digits per channel.
6820     * This means that changing must be at least length 8 (this doesn't check for efficiency reasons), and that the
6821     * first two chars represent the red channel from 0 to 255, then the next two are green, then blue. The alpha
6822     * channel is a special case because it represents alpha values between 0 and 254, and effectively rounds down to
6823     * the nearest even number if an odd number value was somehow given to it. For example, opaque white will be shown
6824     * as "FFFFFFFE", and pure red with 50% alpha will be shown as "FF00007E".
6825     * <br>
6826     * The value of {@code color} should be the same type used internally in libGDX and SquidLib, that is, an ABGR
6827     * packed float that could be passed directly to {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)}.
6828     *
6829     * @param changing a char array that will be changed in place; must not be null and must have length of at least 8
6830     * @param color a color
6831     * @return
6832     */
6833    public static char[] floatToChars(final char[] changing, final float color)
6834    {
6835        final int i = NumberUtils.floatToIntColor(color);
6836        changing[1] = digits[i & 15];
6837        changing[0] = digits[(i >>> 4) & 15];
6838        changing[3] = digits[(i >>> 8) & 15];
6839        changing[2] = digits[(i >>> 12) & 15];
6840        changing[5] = digits[(i >>> 16) & 15];
6841        changing[4] = digits[(i >>> 20) & 15];
6842        changing[7] = digits[(i >>> 24) & 14]; // mask is 14 due to libGDX avoiding floats that can be NaN
6843        changing[6] = digits[i >>> 28];
6844        return changing;
6845    }
6846
6847    /**
6848     * Meant for usage with {@link #floatToChars(char[], float)}, this will take 8 chars from {@code data} and use them
6849     * to construct an int in RGBA8888 format. Some parts of libGDX use and expect RGBA8888 order, such as most
6850     * constructors for Color and {@link Color#set(int)}, while others use ABGR8888 (often with packed floats), like
6851     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)}, which is the fastest and least wasteful way to set
6852     * the current color used by a Batch for tinting.
6853     * @param data a char array that must not be null and must have length of at least 8
6854     * @param offset where to start reading from in data; there must be at least 8 items between offset and data.length
6855     * @return an int in RGBA8888 format
6856     */
6857    public static int charsToRGBA(final char[] data, final int offset)
6858    {
6859        return StringKit.intFromHex(data, offset, Math.min(data.length, offset+8));
6860    }

6922     * Meant for usage with {@link #floatToChars(char[], float)}, this will take 8 chars from {@code data} and use them
6923     * to construct a packed float in ABGR8888 format. Some parts of libGDX use and expect RGBA8888 order, such as most
6924     * constructors for Color and {@link Color#set(int)}, while others use ABGR8888 (often with packed floats), like

6926     * the current color used by a Batch for tinting.
6927     * @param data a CharSequence that must not be null and must have length of at least 8

6929     * @return a float in packed ABGR8888 format

6934        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor(
6935                Integer.reverseBytes(StringKit.intFromHex(data, offset, Math.min(data.length(), offset+8))));
6936    }

6938    /**
6939     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given as 4 RGBA float components. LibGDX expects ABGR format
6940     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
6941     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
6942     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
6943     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
6944     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
6945     * @param r a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for red
6946     * @param g a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for green
6947     * @param b a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for blue
6948     * @param a a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for alpha/opacity
6949     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
6950     */
6951    public static float floatGet(float r, float g, float b, float a)
6952    {
6953        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor(((int)(a * 255) << 24) | ((int)(b * 255) << 16)
6954                | ((int)(g * 255) << 8) | (int)(r * 255));
6955    }
6956
6957    /**
6958     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given an RGBA8888-format long. LibGDX expects ABGR format
6959     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
6960     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
6961     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
6962     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
6963     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
6964     * <br>
6965     * This method is probably not what you want unless you specifically have RGBA8888-format longs that you
6966     * want converted to packed floats. You probably should look at {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)} if
6967     * you have alpha and/or float components, or {@link #floatGetI(int, int, int)} for the common case of the 3 RGB
6968     * components as ints and alpha simply opaque.
6969     * @param c a long with format {@code 32 unused bits, 8 red bits, 8 green bits, 8 blue bits, 7 alpha bits, 1 unused bit}
6970     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
6971     */
6972    public static float floatGet(long c)
6973    {
6974        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor((int)((c >>> 24 & 0xff) | (c >>> 8 & 0xff00) | (c << 8 & 0xff0000)
6975                | (c << 24 & 0xfe000000)));
6976    }

6978    /**
6979     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given an RGBA8888-format int. LibGDX expects ABGR format
6980     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
6981     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
6982     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
6983     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
6984     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
6985     * <br>
6986     * This method is probably not what you want unless you specifically have RGBA8888-format ints that you
6987     * want converted to packed floats. You probably should look at {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)} if
6988     * you have alpha and/or float components, or {@link #floatGetI(int, int, int)} for the common case of the 3 RGB
6989     * components as ints and alpha simply opaque.
6990     * @param c an int with format {@code 8 red bits, 8 green bits, 8 blue bits, 7 alpha bits, 1 unused bit}
6991     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
6992     */
6993    public static float floatGet(int c)
6994    {
6995        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor((c >>> 24 & 0xff) | (c >>> 8 & 0xff00) | (c << 8 & 0xff0000)
6996                | (c << 24 & 0xfe000000));
6997    }

6999    /**
7000     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given as 3 RGB int components, setting alpha to opaque. LibGDX
7001     * expects ABGR format in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR,
7002     * or ARGB. Generally, packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed
7003     * directly to {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setColor(float)} without constructing intermediate
7004     * objects. SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
7005     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
7006     * @param r an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for red
7007     * @param g an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for green
7008     * @param b an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for blue
7009     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
7010     */
7011    public static float floatGetI(int r, int g, int b)
7012    {
7013        return NumberUtils.intToFloatColor((r & 0xff) | (g << 8 & 0xff00) | (b << 16 & 0xff0000)
7014                | 0xfe000000); //rgbToFloatColor((b & 0xff) | (g << 8 & 0xff00) | (r << 16));
7015    }
7016
7017    @SuppressWarnings("NumericOverflow")
7018    public static float lerpFloatColors(final float start, final float end, final float change)
7019    {
7020        final int s = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(start), e = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(end),
7021                rs = (s & 255), gs = (s & 255 << 8) >>> 8, bs = (s & 255 << 16) >>> 16, as = (s & 254 << 24) >>> 24,
7022                re = (e & 255), ge = (e & 255 << 8) >>> 8, be = (e & 255 << 16) >>> 16, ae = (e & 254 << 24) >>> 24;
7023        return NumberUtils.intBitsToFloat(((int)(rs + change * (re - rs)) & 0xff)
7024                | ((int)(gs + change * (ge - gs)) & 0xff) << 8
7025                | (((int)(bs + change * (be - bs)) & 0xff) << 16)
7026                | (((int)(as + change * (ae - as)) & 0xfe) << 24));
7027    }

7029    @Override
7030    public String toString() {
7031        return name + " " + super.toString();
7032    }
7033
7034    public String getName() {
7035        return name;
7036    }
7037
7038    @Override
7039    public boolean equals(Object other) {
7040        return (other instanceof SColor || other instanceof Color) && toIntBits() == ((Color) other).toIntBits();
7041    }
7042
7043    @Override
7044    public int hashCode() {
7045        return  (155 + CrossHash.Wisp.hash(name)) * 31 + toIntBits();
7046    }
